{"source_key":"sha256-300730d11a7046aaae6c4eb40315fa44","record_index":338,"record_hash":"sha256:dd5160cad75b64d88719d98cd91ba0c2c4dfd7b37354f86a26f42232c76fe0ec","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:05:15.955Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 65ace2\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2540\nOutput:\nA reviewer should be able to answer these in under one minute:\n\n- why this trail is related to the PR\n- what the human asked the agent to do\n- what the agent claimed it changed\n- what validation ran, failed, or was skipped\n- which evidence can be expanded\n- what is still uncertain\n\nDefault behavior:\n\n- select the strongest session automatically\n- rank review-target matches above branch-only matches\n- dedupe sessions that match both review and branch targets\n- show highlighted turns first, with chronological expansion available\n- collapse large tool output by default\n- keep overview context visible while browsing session detail\n\nUseful relevance badges:\n\n- `Review match`: the turn observed the PR review target\n- `Branch match`: the turn observed the PR head branch\n- `Validation`: the turn ran a test, build, formatter, or linter\n- `Claim`: the assistant described implementation or validation work\n- `Weak`: branch-only evidence, broad session, or stale/current-env-only signal\n\n## Session Browsing Experience\n\nThe Agent Trail webpage should let a reviewer browse the related agent sessions\nin a user-friendly way.\n\nThe browsing experience should not feel like opening a raw JSON log or a giant\nchat transcript. It should feel like exploring the working history behind the\npull request.\n\nGood session browsing behavior:\n\n- show related sessions as a small list with readable labels, agent/provider,\n  capture time, and relevance reason\n- show turns within a selected session as a compact timeline\n- group records into human request, assistant response, tool call, tool result,\n  and validation blocks\n- collapse noisy tool output by default\n- highlight commands that changed files, ran tests, failed, or produced useful\n  evidence\n- make related branches, reviews, files, and validation attempts easy to scan\n- let the user expand exact transcript records when they need evidence\n- preserve chronological order without forcing\n[TRUNCATED]\nes both review and branch targets\n- refresh and invalidation behavior for cached snapshots\n- detailed UI layout beyond the MVP page contract\n- generated summaries\n- private repository access\n- GitHub OAuth and GitButler workspace auth\n- configurable metadata remotes and arbitrary metadata locations\n- GitHub check-run, app panel, PR description, or bot-comment integration\n- user-controlled session hiding/exclusion before publishing\n- reviewer follow-up questions against the trail\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe first implementation should satisfy:\n\n- route parses `/<owner>/<repo>/pull/<number>` for the Agent Trail domain\n- server verifies the GitHub repository and PR are publicly readable\n- fork PRs return a clear unsupported state\n- first request initializes a bare/cache repository; later requests re-fetch\n- server fetches only `refs/meta/main` for metadata in v1\n- snapshot generation is pinned to the fetched metadata OID\n- lookup searches the PR review target and PR head branch\n- results dedupe sessions/turns and rank review matches above branch-only matches\n- page shows PR identity, snapshot metadata/OID, sessions, match reasons, turn\n  timeline, and expandable evidence\n- branch-only matches are labeled weaker than review matches\n- raw records are available only through bounded drill-down\n- Forge renders only `but-agentlog` redacted public/read projection data\n- tests cover URL parsing, target normalization, review+branch merge/ranking,\n  missing metadata, no matching sessions, and fork PR rejection\n\n## Implementation Boundary\n\n